post_text:
No School Tues. Sept. 8 Due to Widespread Power Outage

Due to widespread power outages impacting thousands of our scholars, families, staff and schools to access internet, the district and school buildings will be closed today. We’ve contacted Puget Sound Energy and do not have an estimated time of repair. As a result, we are cancelling school today, Tuesday, September 8, 2020. All buildings will be closed.

Without power in our neighborhoods for our scholars, families, staff and schools to access internet, they will be disconnected from remote learning

We will provide you an update later today through our automated messaging system.

Kindergarten Update:

Family Connection Conferences that were scheduled for Thursday, September 10, and Friday, September 11 will continue as scheduled. Conferences that were originally scheduled for Wednesday, September 9 will be rescheduled, likely to Monday, September 14. A staff member from your child’s school will reach out to confirm the new appointment.

As a result, the first day of kindergarten instruction will now be Tuesday, September 15.

If you haven’t scheduled your Family Connect Conference, please contact your child’s school.

September is Attendance Awareness Month! Our scholars are starting this year with 100% remote learning, and attendance is a crucial part of success. Check out these tips for supporting your scholar:

• Set up a place for learning
• Create a consistent and predictable routine for learning every day
• Check in regularly with your child
• Model gratitude and celebration
• Make sure your ParentVue account is established to monitor your child’s progress and keep track of attendance at grades.fwps.org
We’re here to support you! Reach out to your child’s teacher or school with any questions or needs. Also, the Continuous Learning 2.0: A Guide for Families is an essential tool for remote learning: www.fwps.org/familyguide
#SchoolEveryday #FWPSGoal2 #EveryDayCounts

post_text:
Starting September 9, 2020 school meal kits will be served every Wednesday!

Funded by the USDA, meals are available for FWPS students and children ages 18 or younger at no cost.

How will the school meals program work?
• We now have 65 locations to pick up meals throughout the district!
• There will be multiple meal pick-up times; the earliest starting at 9:30 a.m. and the latest ending at 6:00 p.m.
• Meal kits include: 5 breakfast and 5 lunches. Scholars will have a choice between a microwavable kit or ready-to-eat kit.
• Parents may pick up for their children ages 18 or younger. Child does not need to be present.
For additional information visit: www.fwps.org/schoolmeals. If you have questions, please call 253-945-5561 or email nutrition@fwps.org.

Childcare registration now open for K-6 grade students!

Act now to sign-up for the 2020-21 Right At School childcare which offers high-quality and flexible care!

With Right at School there is:
• An array of childcare options, including full-day care for K-6 students with access to FWPS’ remote learning this fall.
• Flexibility to build a schedule for the days and parts of the day that you need care.
• Childcare for children with special needs with district support.
• 25% discount for families who qualify for Free & Reduced Meals
• A weekly billing option, and they accept state subsidies.

To register visit https://rightatschool.com/program-finder, or call 1-855-287-2466.

post_text:
GREAT NEWS: Right At School is now offering families who qualify for Free & Reduced Meals a 25% discount for high-quality, flexible 2020-21 school year childcare! Also, full day pricing is reduced to $70.

To access discount registration visit https://rightatschool.com/discounts/. If you believe you qualify and have already registered, please send an email to info@rightatschool.com, or call 855-287-2466.

Also, RAS has adjusted the hours of operation to align with scholar remote learning schedules – see the flyer for details. For more information visit https://rightatschool.com/.

In order to host a program at a school, there is a minimum number of students needed to participate. If the minimum enrollment for an individual school site is not met by August 26, families will be notified on August 31, 2020. At that time, families will have the option to withdraw and/or move their child to the most convenient location that will be providing childcare.

post_text:
The Continuous Learning 2.0 Guide for Families is now available at www.fwps.org/FamilyGuide! We know this is a challenging time, and we want our students and their families to feel safe and prepared as we start a new school year. We’ve heard from many parents about the need for more support and consistency as we approach learning for the 2020-21 school year and this guide reflects that feedback along with guidance from OSPI and DOH, and the work of a 100-member Continuous Learning Plan (CLP) committee, comprised of parents, school and district staff.

This guide is full of valuable information including:
• A day in the life of a scholar
• Schedules
• Attendance and grading information
• Tips for setting your scholar up for success
• Information about who to contact for common questions
• Health and safety protocols
• and more!

Translations and hard copies coming soon!

School Supplies: Check Out What the District Will Be Providing to Scholars This Year

Lists of what will be in the school supply kits ordered by the district are now on the website at www.fwps.org/schoolsupplies.
As you may recall, the district is purchasing school supplies in bulk to offer them at a reduced price or no cost to families. For families who qualify for Free and Reduced Lunch (FRL), the supplies will be at no cost, otherwise it will be $20 per child.
These will be available for pick up near the start of the school year; schedule to be announced soon.

post_text: We are working hard behind the scenes to make sure health and safety is at the forefront in Federal Way Public Schools. Over 100 plexi-glass barriers have been assembled and installed, social distancing stickers have been placed, and there are touch-less thermal temperature scanners being installed at every school office site. Our safety protocols follow the Department of Health guidelines and consider key areas such as social distancing, face coverings and PPE, hand-washing and hygiene, daily symptom checking, HVAC/ventilation and cleaning and disinfecting.

post_text:
Meals for children will continue with the Summer Meals Program June 29 – August 10, 2020!

Every Monday, parents may pick up a week’s worth of free meals (five breakfasts and five lunches) for their children.

Funded by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), “grab and go” meals are available for FWPS scholars and children ages 18 or younger at no cost.

How will the summer meals program work?
• Meal pick up will occur on Mondays only.
• All 10 meals will be provided in one grocery bag and one small box to ease transportation.
• The meals will come with a five-day menu to ensure nourishment is provided for all five days.
• Parents may pick up meals for their children — children do not need to be present.

Meals will be available at 13 sites across the district. The schedule with times and locations can be found here: www.fwps.org/summermeals.

Eligible families: Get help buying food with P-EBT!

We want you to know your student may be eligible for food assistance with the Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) Emergency School Meals Program. Every eligible student may qualify for up $399.

This benefit is for Washington children in grades K-12 who receive free or reduced school meals, OR students who attend a Community Eligibility Provision School: Career Academy, Lake Grove, Mark Twain, Mirror Lake, Olympic View, Open Doors, Panther Lake, Rainier View, Silver Lake, Sunnycrest, or Wildwood.

If your child is not currently approved for free or reduced meals, but you think they may qualify complete an application before June 30, 2020 to be eligible for P-EBT benefits.

The P-EBT application isn’t live yet, but will be available starting June 30, 2020 at www.washingtonconnection.org. Please apply at that time.

Next steps, including how to apply, found here: www.fwps.org/PandemicEBT.

post_text:
We’ve served over 1600 preschool children and families in need!

The switch to remote learning during the Stay Home, Stay Healthy order created an opportunity for the FWPS ECEAP/Head Start program to provide services to scholars and families in a unique way. Although the school environment changed, staff continued to reach out to families on a weekly basis to meet their needs in this new environment.

Although we provided as many resources to families as possible, it was evident that there were additional needs. FWPS reached out to community partners, including We Love Our City, The Emergency Feeding Program, and PC Produce to deliver food and essential supplies directly to families who were unable to access other resources. These partnerships, coupled with private donations, have allowed us to provide food, diapers, hygiene products and cleaning supplies to more than 1600 ECEAP and Head Start children and family members over five weeks!

post_text:
Meals for children will continue with the Summer Meals Program June 29 – August 10, 2020!

Every Monday, parents may pick up a week’s worth of free meals (five breakfasts and five lunches) for their children.

Funded by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), “grab and go” meals are available for FWPS scholars and children ages 18 or younger
at no cost.

How will the summer meals program work?
• Meal pick up will occur on Mondays only.
• All 10 meals will be provided in one grocery bag and one small box to ease transportation.
• The meals will come with a five-day menu to ensure nourishment is provided for all five days.
• Parents may pick up meals for their children — children do not need to be present.

Meals will be available at 13 sites across the district. The schedule with times and locations can be found here: www.fwps.org/summermeals

post_text:
FWPS is leading the Road Map Region in schools recognized for growth!

Last month, 22% percent of our schools were recognized by the State Board of Education, the Educational Opportunity Gap Oversight and Accountability Committee (EOGOAC), and the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction for student achievement growth. This is a significant increase from last year, and it’s the highest percentage of any district in the Road Map Region!

We are #FWPSProud of our success and invite you to read more about the recognition here: https://bit.ly/2TOdO3z

post_text:
Parents are critical partners in their child’s education, and this is true now more than ever. This is why Superintendent Dr. Tammy Campbell continues to engage with families by hosting regular parent Zoom Q&A meetings while school buildings are closed. Earlier today, roughly 180 parents attended a virtual Q&A with Dr. Campbell, where they shared feedback about the current remote learning, and asked questions about end of year activities, and what next school year will look like. Be on the lookout for answers to these questions and an invite for the next virtual parent Q&A session.

If you have a question and were not able to attend today’s meeting, please email comments@fwps.org.

Join us for our first #WEcelebrate in Washington where we'll be celebrating change-makers across the state.

We’re setting out on a virtual road trip across the U.S. to honor the class of 2020: the everyday change-makers who aren’t letting anything stand in the way of them making a difference—not even a pandemic.

From Washington to California you’ll hear from inspiring speakers and performers, plus meet incredible youth and teachers who have been giving back to their communities all year long and who even now have stepped up with new and innovative ways to do good.

Brought to you by: The Allstate Foundation

May 6 at 2:28 PM ·

It's Wonderful Worksite Wednesday!

Help us recognize one of our incredible community partners, World Vision Storehouse in Fife!

ETP would like to spotlight World Vision. World Vision has provided ETP student interns with real-life work experiences in a professional setting. Thank you, World Vision, for all you do for not only the community at large, but specifically the investment you make in each of the ETP World Vision Interns!

post_text:
Thanks to the district’s strong partnerships with organizations like World Vision, we can provide critical support to scholars and families during the pandemic. Our partnership with World Vision includes providing boxes with food and essential supplies to scholars and families in need, and FWPS and World Vision provide staff to help with distribution.

The food box includes enough non-perishable food items to feed a family of 5 for a week. The essentials box includes Clorox wipes, paper towels, World Vision hygiene kits, hand sanitizer, soap, coloring books and a school supply pack. Over the course of 4 weeks, the goal is to serve 400 families in greater Federal Way.

Schools can’t do it alone, and we are grateful for the support!

SCHEDULE UPDATE: Pickup times are extended at all school sites starting Monday, May 4, 2020. Locations remain the same.

Based on the increased demand of our meal program, we are extending meal pickup times at all sites.

As a reminder, meal pickup occurs on Mondays only and includes 5 days’ worth of meals (breakfast and lunch). One exception: Since Monday, May 25 is a holiday (Memorial Day), distribution will occur on Tuesday, May 26.

Find more information including the new schedule on our website: www.fwps.org/meals.

The 2020 #PlanYourPathWA Student Voices Video Contest has launched! We’re giving 5 WA public HS students the chance to earn a $500 scholarship for recording a video about their education & career dreams.

post_text:
We’re doing our part to help those fighting COVID-19 on the front lines – our healthcare workers and first responders.

Through a partnership with Teach For America we loaned a 3D printer to support Maker Mask, a Seattle non-profit creating medically endorsed, reusable protective masks using 3D printers. You can read more about Maker Mask’s efforts around the world, in this article, https://bit.ly/2yQHWDG

We also donated 900 medical masks and 25,000 pairs of gloves to the Puget Sound Educational Service District, which is providing donated supplies to local health care providers. #WeGotThisWashington
shared_text:
GEEKWIRE.COM
Maker Mask launches in Seattle using 3D-printing technology to produce protective gear

post_text: How impressive is this? TAF at Saghalie 9th grade scholar Nate Medisky performs some inorganic solutions chemistry at home (under the supervision of his parents, of course). post_text: Did you know CHI Franciscan and other health care facilities in Federal Way are offering free virtual care? Find out more on our Community Resources page. https://www.fwps.org/Page/7540
shared_text:
CHI Franciscan
April 8 at 10:31 AM ·

We are currently offering FREE Virtual Urgent Care visits for anyone exhibiting mild COVID-19 symptoms such as fever, cough or respiratory problems. Visits available 24/7 from the comfort of your home. Visit franciscanvirtualcare.org and enter code COVID19 when requesting care.

If your symptoms are severe such as high fever, shortness of breath or difficulty breathing, visit your nearest Emergency Department.

post_text: During National Public Health Week, we’d like to thank the many healthcare workers, including some of our very own FWPS parents, for all you’re doing to help save lives during this pandemic. We appreciate you! If you know a healthcare worker, please thank them in the comments below.
shared_text:
Public Health - Seattle & King County
April 8 at 10:58 AM ·

As our community faces the pandemic, public health and healthcare professionals are working nonstop throughout King County to save lives in the fight against COVID-19.

We want to say thank you — from everyone in King County, Washington - Government, Public Health - Seattle & King County, and our community — to all public health and healthcare professionals, every day and especially now.

April 6-12 is National Public Health Week. Over the last several weeks, we've all seen firsthand why public health matters.

The courage, professionalism and service of public health and healthcare professionals deserves our deepest gratitude and admiration.

We also acknowledge the sacrifices of public health and healthcare professionals. Our frontline workers cannot stay home with loved ones or stay 6 feet away from sick patients. They put themselves in harm's way to help keep the rest of us safe.

All public health and healthcare professionals working in King County, throughout Washington State, across the United States and around the world have our gratitude. 🧡

post_text:
While schools are closed, we continue to focus on supporting our scholars with their learning. At the start of the closure, we mailed home standards- based lessons and learning activities for scholars to practice their learning. Students should continue to work on these through April 17, 2020.
Beginning April 20, we will provide additional remote learning options. We’ve created a remote learning guide for parents outlining what remote learning is and what types of activities and lessons you can expect to see. It’s attached and can be found on our website at: https://bit.ly/2V7ltd3.

post_text:
Governor Inslee announced school buildings are closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year, in order to slow the spread of COVID-19. While our school buildings are closed, we will continue to provide remote instruction to scholars through the end of the school year in June. Parents may reach out to their child's school principal and teachers for continued support for their child's learning.

Learn more about how we are supporting continued learning from home, the meals program, and more in Superintendent Campbell’s letter on our website: https://www.fwps.org/Page/7537.

Spring Break for Federal Way Public Schools is next week, April 6–10.

Some staff will be working during the break to support child care, the meals program and district operations. “Grab and go” meals for children will continue to be available for pickup at the following sites: https://www.fwps.org/Page/7460 .

While schools have been closed, FWPS staff have supported scholars with their learning using standards-based activities and lessons. We’ll resume remote learning on Monday, April 13, 2020.

post_text:
One way Superintendent Dr. Tammy Campbell is leading the effort to stay connected while schools are closed is by hosting two virtual Q&A sessions with:

21 seniors to check in with them, hear their questions, get their input on graduation, technology access, how we can support, and more. We are committed to supporting seniors in staying on track to graduate this year.

540 FWPS teachers and support staff to go deeper into the continuous learning plan. This helped clarify questions and take feedback from staff who are all in to support scholars with their learning during the closure.

It’s not too late to join the 22,254 people who viewed last week’s e-newsletter! It’s a great way to stay updated during the school closure. Soon, it will provide news from our schools. With 96% of Americans owning a cellphone and over two-thirds accessing the internet on mobile devices, this e-newsletter allows us to take on timely, eco-friendly approaches that embrace our parents’ and community members’ growing use of accessing information online.

Parents and staff will start receiving the weekly e-newsletters via email. If you are a community member and would like to sign up, email comments@fwps.org.

From the words of Dr. Seuss, "The more that you read, the more things you will know. The more that you learn, the more places you'll go." Reading books is a great way to keep students #LearningAtHome!

As a friendly reminder, FWPS students in grades K-12 have access to online resources and eBooks through King County Library System. Simply visit www.kcls.org/students, enter the account number (your student’s school ID number preceded by number 210) and password (the last 4 digits of your student’s school ID). For more information, visit our website: https://www.fwps.org/Page/7493

post_text:
Based on the governor’s proclamation, and the unprecedented nature of the COVID-19 pandemic, FWPS is closing beginning Monday, March 16 to Friday, April 24, 2020. This is to help “flatten the curve” of the rate of infection. Without these restrictions, the rate of infection would overwhelm the health care system.

All schools in the district will be closed during this time. Student Led Conferences previously scheduled for March 19 and 20 are cancelled.

We know this closure will have an impact on our staff, families and community. More information about childcare, meals, and learning from home is available at https://bit.ly/39OczHg .

We know there are more questions, and we will be spending the next days and weeks to respond to many of these questions. We are actively working with the Office of the Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI) to understand how this extended closure may impact the school year calendar, testing, graduation, and more.

post_text: Our FWPS scholars recently served as pages for one week at the Washington State Legislature. Pages perform a wide variety of responsibilities from presenting the flags to distributing amendments on the Senate/House floor. They also contribute to the efficient operation of the Legislature, receive daily civics instruction, draft their own bills and participate in mock committee hearings. Check out how to be a page in the House here: http://bit.ly/1wlSB1b, and in the Senate here: http://bit.ly/2jW0tVG. #WALeg

post_text: It’s National School Counseling Week! Our #SchoolCounselors and College and Career Specialists support scholars with academic, college/career and social/emotional development. We celebrate their hard work, dedication and the tremendous impact they have on helping our scholars achieve their dreams. #NSCW2020
